CHARLES SULLIVAN: We'll talk.

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:51.712
Yes?

00:48:51.712 --> 00:48:53.590
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:48:53.590 --> 00:48:55.540
AUDIENCE: So it's
kind of interesting

00:48:55.540 --> 00:48:59.540
how Cambridge sort of went from
vast expanses of farmland slash

00:48:59.540 --> 00:49:03.160
nothing into house
upon house upon house.

00:49:03.160 --> 00:49:06.400
I'm wondering if you could
elaborate a little bit on how

00:49:06.400 --> 00:49:09.190
sort of the ownership
worked for these marshes

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:11.390
and even the river parts
that got filled in.

00:49:11.390 --> 00:49:13.660
Was there someone who
just was extraordinarily

00:49:13.660 --> 00:49:16.400
lucky who owned all that
land and got to sell it off?

00:49:16.400 --> 00:49:20.440
Or how does ownership work when
they create land like that?

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:23.590
CHARLES SULLIVAN: Well, if
you remember the slide that

00:49:23.590 --> 00:49:28.780
had all the loyalist estates
on it, that one showed you

00:49:28.780 --> 00:49:30.970
areas where real
estate development was

00:49:30.970 --> 00:49:35.170
relatively measured and
carefully organized.

00:49:35.170 --> 00:49:40.360
So that was represented
capital to those land owners,

00:49:40.360 --> 00:49:43.840
and they would carefully lay
out streets and sell off lots

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:46.060
and try to do it in sequence.

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:49.580
Other areas where
there were farms,

00:49:49.580 --> 00:49:53.080
it was divided up and pretty
much sold off at random.

00:49:53.080 --> 00:49:55.120
There's this whole process.

00:49:55.120 --> 00:49:59.440
There's no central planning
of streets in Cambridge

00:49:59.440 --> 00:50:01.700
until the 20th century.

00:50:01.700 --> 00:50:05.800
So the streets would be laid
out by the property developers.

00:50:05.800 --> 00:50:08.050
They would try to
work with each other.

00:50:08.050 --> 00:50:10.990
Typically they'd sell
lots, two or three lots

00:50:10.990 --> 00:50:13.360
at a time, at most,
to a carpenter who

00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:17.200
would build the houses on spec,
live in one until he sold it,

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:19.480
and then buy another
two or three lots.

00:50:19.480 --> 00:50:23.590
So it's a pretty
disorganized organic process.

00:50:23.590 --> 00:50:26.830
It's not centrally
located, centrally planned.

00:50:26.830 --> 00:50:29.980
Nothing like, you know,
Levittown comes to mind.

00:50:29.980 --> 00:50:33.220
But you know nothing like
organized suburban development

00:50:33.220 --> 00:50:39.220
except Coolidge
Hill and Larchwood

00:50:39.220 --> 00:50:41.440
in West Cambridge
in the 20th century

00:50:41.440 --> 00:50:43.810
were small, planned suburbs.

00:50:43.810 --> 00:50:46.095
Everything else
is kind of random.

00:50:46.095 --> 00:50:47.470
AUDIENCE: How
early would you say

00:50:47.470 --> 00:50:51.460
was all of the land privately
owned in some respects?

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:53.800
CHARLES SULLIVAN: Privately
owned as opposed to?

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:57.230
AUDIENCE: As opposed to land no
one has settled on yet, right?

00:50:57.230 --> 00:50:59.230
Was that back in the
1600s, basically?

00:50:59.230 --> 00:51:01.960
CHARLES SULLIVAN:
Land was granted out.

00:51:01.960 --> 00:51:04.610
Some of it was owned in common.

00:51:04.610 --> 00:51:05.850
It was, well, let's say--

00:51:05.850 --> 00:51:09.910
in 1630, it was all owned in
common by the Massachusetts Bay

00:51:09.910 --> 00:51:10.650
Company.

00:51:10.650 --> 00:51:13.570
And so it was
divided into towns.

00:51:13.570 --> 00:51:18.220
Towns would organize
as parishes, actually,

00:51:18.220 --> 00:51:20.190
and as proprietors.

00:51:20.190 --> 00:51:21.880
In Cambridge, there
were the proprietors

00:51:21.880 --> 00:51:26.500
of common lands, group of
citizens that were authorized

00:51:26.500 --> 00:51:31.090
to divide public land and give
it out to existing property

00:51:31.090 --> 00:51:31.930
owners.

00:51:31.930 --> 00:51:37.060
So that was complete by 1750.

00:51:37.060 --> 00:51:40.300
After that, there was almost
no more public land left.

00:51:40.300 --> 00:51:42.486
So every scrap was
privately owned.

00:51:42.486 --> 00:51:44.110
AUDIENCE: So, for
example, the mudflats

00:51:44.110 --> 00:51:45.970
that became MIT,
who were they owned

00:51:45.970 --> 00:51:47.560
by before they were drained?

00:51:47.560 --> 00:51:48.518
CHARLES SULLIVAN: Well.

00:51:48.518 --> 00:51:55.390
The flats-- in Massachusetts,
you can own tidelands out

00:51:55.390 --> 00:51:57.280
to the low tide line.

00:51:57.280 --> 00:52:00.440
And so they didn't
have much value,

00:52:00.440 --> 00:52:02.700
but you could get title to them.

00:52:02.700 --> 00:52:05.500
And an individual did.

00:52:05.500 --> 00:52:07.410
A guy named Charles Davenport--

00:52:07.410 --> 00:52:11.130
had a factory further
down on Main Street--

00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:13.750
thought he saw a lot of
potential in the tidelands.

00:52:13.750 --> 00:52:18.400
And he's the one that organized
a company to build the seawall

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:19.910
and fill in those flats.

00:52:19.910 --> 00:52:24.370
But he was buying them for
pennies in the 1860s and '70s

00:52:24.370 --> 00:52:27.100
and assembling all of that
tideland so that then he

00:52:27.100 --> 00:52:28.979
could do a major development.

00:52:28.979 --> 00:52:31.270
Where MIT is, it was supposed
to be a neighborhood that

00:52:31.270 --> 00:52:33.370
would mirror Boston's Back Bay.

00:52:33.370 --> 00:52:34.480
That's a whole other talk.

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:37.420
But you know, Back Bay--

00:52:37.420 --> 00:52:37.960
same thing.

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:42.520
Seawall-- filled in behind the
sea wall, straight streets laid

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:48.285
out, lots sold on a
consistent, planned basis.

00:52:48.285 --> 00:52:50.410
They were trying to do the
same thing in Cambridge,

00:52:50.410 --> 00:52:51.970
but didn't work.

00:52:51.970 --> 00:52:55.030
And MIT came along
and scooped it up.

00:52:55.030 --> 00:52:56.372
Thank goodness.

00:52:56.372 --> 00:52:58.300
AUDIENCE: And south
of east Cambridge,

00:52:58.300 --> 00:53:00.715
it was bought up by a
development company.

00:53:00.715 --> 00:53:02.440
And they planned it all out.

00:53:02.440 --> 00:53:03.890
So it was a bigger area.

00:53:03.890 --> 00:53:06.040
And you got more
regular streets,

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:08.760
but then they sold it off.

00:53:08.760 --> 00:53:10.760
